window.POSTS = [{"n": 1, "title": "Six Trade Brands, One Conversation, No Scripts", "url": "/blog/six-trade-brands-one-conversation-no-scripts", "type": "News / event", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["When we decided to commission primary research into the role of creativity in construction marketing, we always knew the report was only part of the story.", "Data tells you what. A room full of people who live and breathe this sector every day tells you why and more importantly, what to do about it.", "So when Built for the Trade launched in Birmingham last week, we didn't just publish a report. We gathered thirteen senior marketing leaders from across the trade and built environment sector, sat them down together, and asked them to be honest.", "**The guest list mattered**", "We were joined by representatives from some of the most respected brands operating in the trade sector right now; Crown Paints, Wavin, Mitsubishi Electric, City Plumbing, Clifton Trade Bathrooms, and Tradesman Saver. Between them, the attendees represented decades of experience marketing to tradespeople across plumbing, heating, decorating, bathrooms, drainage, insurance and beyond.", "A structured conversation guided by the research findings about what's working, what isn't, and what the trade sector needs to do differently when it comes to creative marketing.", "**We'd been having this conversation in private for too long**", "The honest answer is that we've been having versions of this conversation with clients and prospects for years in meeting rooms, at trade shows, over coffee. The question of whether creativity genuinely moves trade audiences, or whether this sector is too rational and too loyalty-driven for marketing to make a real difference, comes up constantly.", "Bringing competitors and peers into the same room, people who rarely get the chance to compare notes honestly felt like the right way to take the conversation somewhere more useful than a white paper ever could on its own.", "**We were deliberate about the timing**", "Hosting the roundtable alongside one of the sector's biggest annual gatherings in the InstallerSHOW wasn't accidental. It meant the people in the room had already spent the day (or were just about to) immersed in the trade, seeing products demonstrated, talking to suppliers, watching the industry do what it does. That context kept the conversation grounded. We weren't theorising about tradespeople from a conference room. The audience we were discussing was, quite literally, just outside the door.", "**We're not done yet**", "We'll be publishing a full write-up of the discussion, the themes that emerged, the points of tension, and the practical conclusions the room landed on in the coming weeks. It goes well beyond the research findings and into territory that we think will be genuinely useful for anyone responsible for marketing to trades.", "In the meantime, the Built for the Trade report itself is available to download now here. If it raises questions you'd like to explore further, about your own brand, your creative strategy, or how you're currently showing up for your trade audience, we'd love to hear from you."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 2, "title": "Marketing with a Merchant Mindset", "url": "/blog/marketing-with-a-merchant-mindset", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "Subtitle: And why it's your biggest advantage.", "paras": ["Walk into most trade outlets and you'll see the same thing: promotional posters fighting for attention, supplier POS stacked three deep, wayfinding that makes no sense, and pricing messages shouting over each other.", "It looks busy. It feels chaotic. And somewhere in all that noise, your actual value proposition has gone missing. It's an identity crisis that can't be solved by new signage or a fixture reshuffle alone.", "Not all merchants can clearly articulate what they stand for. So they try to be everything at once: a trusted adviser, a price leader, a digital innovator, a relationship builder. The result? Your trade customers get confused and your marketing becomes a defensive exercise.", "And right now, with the BMF reporting a stagnant market and volumes up but prices falling, you can't afford to waste energy on activity that doesn't build towards something coherent.", "**In a league of their own**", "Trade merchants exist in an identity gap. You're not a global soft drinks brand with emotional budgets and years to build salience. Neither are you a top five supermarket with promotional muscle and basket economics. Yet most merchant marketing strategies borrow from one camp or the other.", "Brand thinking tells you to play the long game, tell stories and build emotion. Retail thinking demands you shift volume, promote price and drive footfall today. And you're stuck defending tactics that don't fit neatly into either framework, while being judged on metrics designed for businesses that look nothing like yours.", "**Trade customers think differently**", "When your in-store experience is cluttered with competing promotions and your digital offering exists, but isn't embedded in how trade customers run their business, you're adding cognitive load they don't need.", "They expect speed, without friction. Expertise when needed, not generic product-pushing. Fair pricing, not constant discounting that erodes trust. Digital convenience, without losing human contact.", "When we strip it back with the trades, the same themes come up: \"They're always open when I need them\", \"They usually have what I want\", \"They sort problems quickly\", \"They don't muck me about on price\", \"I trust them\".", "The BMF's Branch of the Future report makes this explicit: customer expectations around convenience, personalisation, expertise and sustainability determine what branches need to deliver. Ignore that shift and you're competing solely on proximity and price.", "**Embracing the merchant mindset**", "A merchant mindset is being clear about who you serve, how you help your customers, and why you exist. That is; availability, expertise, reliability and relationship. A merchant mindset takes those truths and builds everything around them: the branch layout, what gets space, how staff are briefed, how digital is positioned, and how you talk about value without turning into a never-ending clearance sale.", "**From chaos to coherence**", "Reclaiming your identity doesn't start with a rebrand. It starts with clarity. Decide what you want to be famous for among the trades you serve. Then let that dictate what stays, what goes and what changes. You'll soon see the store layout becomes a tool, not a battleground. Promotional spaces become a curated edit of what fits your promise.", "Online and offline stop competing. If you define digital as another branch, open 24/7, your KPIs change. You design the journey around the same working habits you see at the counter, and you brief staff to actively use digital as part of their everyday service. The goal is simple: the same offering, accessed through different doors.", "**Where an agency actually earns its keep**", "This is where a creative agency that understands merchants can be useful, not by turning up with more stuff to cram into the branch, but by taking things away, helping you articulate precisely who you are for and what you stand for. And giving you the language you can use in the boardroom and at the bottom line, not just in a brand book.", "The skill is in translating that stance into environments, campaigns and digital journeys that respect how trades really behave. Smarter ways to show off your availability, make your expertise visible, prove your reliability and bring your relationships to life. Done properly, creativity stops being an indulgence and becomes an action-provoking asset.", "**Choosing clarity over complexity**", "The most successful merchants over the next few years won't be the loudest or the most aggressive discounters. They'll be the ones whose branches feel like they've been designed around real working days; whose opening hours, stock discipline and digital tools save time rather than steal it; whose teams behave consistently because they're not guessing what the brand stands for.", "Stop copying the brands. Stop copying the retailers. Own the merchant mindset and work with partners who understand how to turn it from a phrase into a living, breathing experience for the trade. That's where the steady growth and success is hiding."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 3, "title": "Beyond the basics: How private label builds better brands", "url": "/blog/beyond-the-basics-how-private-label-builds-better-brands", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["For decades, private label was seen as the cheap and cheerful 'value aisle'. Super-functional products sitting at the bottom of the shelf, giving customers a price-sensitive alternative to the pricey big brands.", "They weren't always the contenders that they are today. Their journey in the UK supermarket from bargain-bin staples to serious shelf challengers began way back in the 1960s and 70s. Kwik-Save's 'No Frills' and Fine Fare's lurid and unmissable yellow packaging set the pace in the race to the bottom for grocery essentials in supermarkets. And who can forget the eternal optimism of the Happy Shopper range?", "Eventually Tesco, Sainsbury's, Asda, Morrisons, even Waitrose, picked up the budget baton developing brands like Just Essentials, Stockwell, Everyday Value, Stamford Street and Savers; all based on value rather than quality.", "In FMCG today, private label now flexes its sizeable muscles in both directions serving both value-conscious and premium-seeking consumers. 'Taste the Difference', 'Extra Special', 'Finest', 'The Best' and 'Irresistible', 'Specially Selected' and 'Deluxe' all point to supermarkets using private label to lead categories with bolder designs, clear brand stories and better quality.", "So while all that's been happening at your local supermarket, in the Built Environment, it's been exactly the same; private label strategies are no longer an afterthought. In fact, planned and executed well they are a powerful lever for growth, differentiation, innovation and category leadership.", "At Workhouse, we've seen this first-hand. We've helped numerous clients develop their portfolio of private label brands that not only held their own against big-name competitors, but in many cases actually redefined their categories. From adhesives, paint and tools to outdoor porcelain and luxury vinyl, private label has become a strategic weapon for many of our clients. But just like our FMCG counterparts, the journey isn't without its challenges:", "**It's a trust thing** — Private label has long carried the stigma of being low quality, the 'cheaper alternative'. In technical or trade-driven sectors like the Built Environment, that stigma can be hard to shake. Installers and professionals often default to the brands they know, while consumers understandably play it safe, lacking the confidence to choose a name they don't recognise.", "**Playing in functional categories** — Adhesives, tools, flooring systems, building materials in general: like it or not, these categories can struggle to fire the imagination. The risk is that private label becomes the generic, unmemorable option in a sea of functional products.", "**What do we want?** — Retailers may see private label as a route to margin, while trade professionals want reliability, and consumers want reassurance. A successful strategy needs to deliver for all three simultaneously.", "**The potential of private label** — Despite the challenges, the opportunity is huge, especially for retailers and manufacturers in the Built Environment.", "- *Category leadership* — Private label allows retailers to shape categories on their terms. By filling gaps, offering tiered ranges and defining new quality benchmarks, they can set the pace rather than follow global suppliers.\n- *Margin and loyalty* — A strong private label portfolio captures greater margin and ties customer loyalty more tightly to the retailer. Instead of building value into someone else's brand, private label locks that value into your own ecosystem.\n- *Agility and innovation* — A private label brand can move faster than a global competitor, responding quickly to trends like from sustainability to design-led outdoor living. That agility makes them more relevant to today's consumer and trade audiences.\n- *Trust and credibility* — When executed with creativity, private label brands stop looking like 'brand copies' and become credible, trusted choices in their own right. In sectors where there's a choice, that trust is priceless.", "**The benefits of brand-led private label** — A private label's potential relies on creative brand thinking. Without it, private labels remain a vacuous and voiceless commodity. With it, private label can develop into a portfolio of distinctive assets. A solid creative strategy and ambition must be put in place from the beginning: Naming and identity that are thoroughly researched and feel as considered as any national brand. Messaging and positioning that signal expertise, quality and credibility. Design systems that build consistency across a portfolio, while giving each brand its own voice. Storytelling that elevates a product or range from a functional purchase to an aspirational choice.", "When a portfolio of private label brands is underpinned by a forward-thinking, category-defining strategy, it does more than drive sales. It changes how customers see the retailer itself; from a distributor of other people's products to a trusted brand builder in its own right.", "**Case in point** — Topps Tiles is a perfect case in point that demonstrates the transformative power of strategically-led private label. Working together with the Topps team, we built an inspiring range across the entire customer journey: Regener8 adhesives (a performance-led range designed to instil confidence in professionals); Dex Tools (a tool brand that empowers installers with reliability and precision); Everscape outdoor porcelain (an aspirational lifestyle brand that owned outdoor living); Pronto LVT (a modern flooring solution built around speed, simplicity and style).", "Each brand has a clear positioning, a creative platform and a story that means something to its audience. As a portfolio, it gives Topps Tiles the ability to own the category conversation. These brands didn't just fill shelf space, they've been the catalyst for a seismic shift in perception and anchored Topps Tiles as a trusted retailer and an innovator. By 2023–24, approximately 80% of their tile ranges and related products were either exclusive or own-brand.", "**Looking ahead** — Over the next five years, across the Built Environment, private label will only grow in importance. Economic pressures are driving customers to seek out value. Sustainability concerns are driving them to look for reassurance. And digital-first, review-hungry audiences are rewriting what trust looks like. Retailers and manufacturers who embrace private label as a strategic brand-building opportunity, rather than a margin exercise, will have a distinct competitive advantage. Those who don't, risk being left behind. At Workhouse, we believe the future of private label is creative, strategic and disruptive."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 4, "title": "When Trade Equity Doesn't Travel", "url": "/blog/when-trade-equity-doesnt-travel", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Functional attributes; easy, durable, reliable are hard-won in the trade. The assumption that they carry the same weight with consumers is understandable. It's also one of the most common mistakes a brand-led product business can make.", "There's a particular confidence that comes from genuine trade dominance. When installers, specifiers and merchants trust a brand, when \"easy\" or \"reliable\" have been proven on thousands of jobs, in thousands of homes, it feels like a foundation broad enough to build anything on. And in many respects, it is. Trade loyalty is extraordinarily hard to earn and even harder to dislodge.", "But trade equity and consumer desire are built from different materials. For the installer, \"easy\" resolves a real professional anxiety: will this product go in cleanly, perform reliably, and not generate a callback? Those are high-stakes functional questions, and a brand that answers them consistently earns deep trust. The word \"easy\" does genuine work there.", "The consumer arrives at the same category with a different set of anxieties and a different set of aspirations. Homeowners now research bathroom and kitchen decisions with a seriousness that would have been unusual a decade ago. They arrive with mood boards, finish preferences, a considered aesthetic. The tap or tile they choose isn't just infrastructure. It's part of a space that reflects something about them. In that context, \"easy\" lands differently. Not wrong, exactly. Just incomplete and in a design-conscious market, incomplete reads as unremarkable.", "What makes a brand the easy choice for a professional is precisely what makes it feel like a default choice to a consumer. The same word. Two entirely different reactions.", "This isn't a criticism of functional positioning, it's an observation about its limits. The brands that navigate this successfully don't abandon their trade equity. They build a second layer on top of it: one that speaks to aspiration, design intent, and the emotional dimension of living with a product every day. The plumber cares about fitting it. The homeowner cares about living with it. Both matter. But they require different conversations.", "The question is whether the brand is having both or whether the consumer is getting the trade conversation by default, because nobody has designed a different one. Competitors investing in design aspiration, sustainability credentials, and smart integration are creating desire in territory that functional claims can't reach. That gap, left unmanaged, tends to widen.", "There's a version of \"easy\" that does carry consumer aspiration; the ease of living well, the effortlessness of a space that just works, the quiet confidence of a product that was clearly designed with care. That's not a departure from the positioning. It's a maturation of it. But it requires a deliberate creative decision, not an assumption that the trade story will do the job on its own."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 5, "title": "The Generation Game: Mind the gap", "url": "/blog/the-generation-game-mind-the-gap", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["It's no secret that a seismic demographic shift is underway across the trades in the Built Environment.", "There's a well-documented and increasingly concerning skills gap between the time-served, over-50s; plumbers, decorators, electricians, fitters who stand by brand loyalty, long-standing supplier relationships and bulk deals - and 'Generation Toolbelt'; an emerging wave of digitally native, Gen Z tradespeople who are much more open to experimentation, driven by peer reviews and responsive deliveries. For product manufacturers, it's both a challenge and an opportunity. How do you position your brand to resonate with these two different mindsets?", "**Why the gap?** A perfect storm of demographic shifts, cultural perception of trades, policy failure, and industry inertia has meant a whole generation being nudged away from trades, creating the huge vacuum in trade talent we see today. The fight is all too real when your most closely guarded secret is your electrician's phone number. Or you're willing to wait two years for 'your' plumber to tile the en-suite.", "According to Checkatrade's UK Trade Skills Index report, 35% of construction workers are over 50. When retirement is both sudden and imminent, the industry will soon lose up to a third of its skilled labour - along with decades of knowledge and experience, in one generation. The report highlighted that the home improvement and repair sector will grow by 40% over the next decade and that the UK would need to find 1.3 million new skilled tradespeople and over 350,000 new apprentices to deliver the Government's housing and net zero targets.", "But all is not lost. Gen Z are starting to form an orderly queue for a career in the trades. As the B&Q The Way We Live Now report points out, there is a rise in younger individuals, motivated by factors like financial independence, job flexibility and the avoidance of student debt. Young people are also increasingly starting to see trades as future-proof careers that AI can't easily replace.", "**The over-50s: brand loyalists** — They've built their careers on trust and reliability. They know what works, and they stick with it. Their buying habits are based on recognition, trust and consistency. Supplier relationships are personal and long-term; promotions that reward bulk purchases and long-term planning resonate.", "**'Generation Toolbelt': the digital natives** — They're entrepreneurial, tech-savvy and community-driven. Not afraid to try something new, based on innovation or peer buzz. You'll only get one chance to deliver on your bold claims, but if you capture their imagination, they'll put it out on their socials. They shop around, pay attention to reviews and trust their community. Orders are on-demand, delivered to the job, so bulk has no pull.", "**Bridging the gap** — When you choose the right tool, your brand can speak to both:\n1. **Pride in craft and competence** — Both value skill, mastery and pride in doing the job right. Layer your language to celebrate craftsmanship; tap into professional standards (respect/reputation for older; credibility/progress for younger).\n2. **Tools, tech and training** — Ease, efficiency and time-saving tools are appreciated across both. Position tech as a tool to make their job easier, not a threat. Avoid over-hyping innovation without real benefit.\n3. **Community and recognition** — Both respond to community content showing achievements and challenges ('Pro of the Month', 'Tools of the Trade'). Older skews Facebook/YouTube; Gen Z skews TikTok/Insta.\n4. **Trust in the brand** — Trust, quality and reliability remain top buying drivers. Trade endorsements, reviews, performance tests, durability metrics and confident warranties build the trust factor. Invest in real-job photography, not over-polished stock.\n5. **Safety, health and wellbeing** — Older tradespeople think long-term wear and tear; Gen Z care about mental health, burnout and balance. Build emotional intelligence and genuine empathy into your brand.", "**Brands that build bridges** find commonality in deep-seated human principles: Pride in the craft (identity-based) · Tools that work smarter (results-driven) · Community (peer recognition) · Trustworthy brand (consistency, performance) · Wellbeing and safety (empathy)."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 6, "title": "Language: Your Silent Sales Rep", "url": "/blog/language-your-silent-sales-rep", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "Subtitle: How the right words and tone in the Built Environment drives buying decisions.", "paras": ["The built environment speaks to us. Not just through its physical presence, its network of services, technology and products - but through its words. From the brazen headline on a billboard to the subtle reassurance of a product description, every syllable shapes perception, builds trust and nudges action. The right words don't just describe, they persuade. They don't just inform, they resonate. The difference between forgettable and formidable often comes down to the words.", "**Make a name for yourself** — In property development, a well-chosen name can elevate a building from a physical structure to an aspirational lifestyle. There's a difference between '22 The Edge' and '22 High Street'. 'Harbour Lights' sells a shimmering waterfront dream; 'The Canopy' suggests lush, secluded greenery. A product name can transform a commodity into a coveted choice — the difference between 'Standard White Paint' and Farrow & Ball's 'All White'. Rory Sutherland: \"people don't buy products, they buy better versions of themselves\" — which is why B&Q's 'GoodHome' outperforms competitors, and Crown's 'CRAFTED™' isn't just paint; it's warmth, heritage and craftsmanship in a can. A 'Premium Brass Tap' is functional, but 'Heritage Victorian Mixer' tells a story. Mark Ritson: \"Your brand is a story, and the name is the title, so make it a page-turner.\"", "**Headlines that hook** — Your headline has seconds to capture attention. Dave Trott: \"People ignore boring. They always have, they always will.\" Topps Tiles' 'The UK's biggest tile specialist' is simple, confident and reassuring — a promise, not just a claim. Crown Paints reframes 'durable exterior paint' as 'Love your home for longer'; B&Q's 'Make your house a home' taps aspiration, not maintenance. Worcester Bosch turns 'regular servicing is advised' into 'Regular servicing keeps your home warm without the worry'. Tredaire sells underlay that 'Feels like nothing on earth'. Different channels demand different approaches — a trade brochure boasts 'BS EN-compliant copper piping'; on Instagram the same product becomes 'The pro plumber's secret to leak-free joints'.", "**Building trust** — For trade buyers, language must balance technical precision with approachability. 'High-performance adhesive for heavy-duty applications' is accurate but flat; Ardex offers 'The grip you need, without the wait'. Research shows headlines with emotional triggers outperform generic ones by up to 40%. 'Luxury city living' is forgettable; 'A sanctuary above the chaos' creates a visceral pull. Headlines can promise transformation ('Live where the city can't keep up'), spark curiosity, or trigger urgency ('Last two apartments remaining').", "**Tune your tone** — In an industry where purchases are high-stakes and trust is paramount, tone of voice is your silent sales rep. Trust is built through consistency, clarity and empathy. A disjointed tone confuses; a distinct, cohesive voice reassures.", "**Adopt and adapt** — Language shape-shifts to platforms. A 48-sheet poster demands brevity ('Your view starts here.'); brochures weave a narrative; social thrives on conversational hooks. Adaptation isn't diluting your tone, it's flexing it.", "**The last word** — Copywriting is the ultimate ROI multiplier. In the built environment, language is the bridge between interest and action. Not clever words, just the right words. Neil Patel: \"The most effective marketing doesn't feel like marketing. It feels like a conversation.\" The best copy doesn't just sell spaces, it sells the ambitions, aspirations and life that goes on inside them — turning browsers into buyers, buildings into lasting legacies, and supplies into sales."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 7, "title": "Assume no-one cares", "url": "/blog/assume-no-one-cares", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "Subtitle: The 95:5 rule and why you should be building 'mental availability' to put your brand top of mind in the Built Environment.", "paras": ["**What Is the 95:5 Rule?** Roughly only 5% of your target audience are actively looking to buy at any given time. The other 95% are out of market. Not ready. But they will be, eventually — and when they are, you want your brand right there, top of mind. The concept was developed by Professor John Dawes at the Ehrenberg-Bass Institute and popularised by LinkedIn's B2B Institute. Its implications are huge for the Built Environment, where purchase cycles are long and infrequent and buying is complex with big-ticket items.", "**Chasing the 5%** — Most marketing in the Built Environment is geared to short-term wins; lead gen, promotions, conversion campaigns. But focusing solely on the 5% who are ready to buy is like fishing in a puddle when there's an ocean nearby. The real opportunity lies in the 95% who will need you someday. The challenge: making sure they think of you when they do.", "**Where is everybody?** — Most of your future revenue comes from buyers who aren't ready today. In construction, engineering or materials supply there are numerous stakeholders — architects, contractors, installers, surveyors and procurement — all with different priorities and timelines. If you're not already on the mental shortlist when they buy, you're playing catch-up.", "**Building Mental Availability** — Coined by Professor Byron Sharp and Jenni Romaniuk (Ehrenberg-Bass). Mental availability isn't just awareness — it's being the first name that comes to mind in a buying situation. Key principles:\n- **Read the Room** — Differentiation is critical: be *meaningfully* different, owning an idea, tone or perspective that resonates. Remove the 'brand manager blinkers' and see the world through the customer's eyes.\n- **Explore Deeper Connections** — Emotional connections linger long after rational arguments fade. B2B doesn't have to be dry — in fact it should never be. Brands that refuse to play it safe break through and command premium pricing.\n- **Build Fluency** — Distinctive brand assets (logo, typeface, colour palette, endline, product shape, jingle) are critical mental shortcuts — the 'do they know it's me?' test. Think golden arches, the meerkat, the Netflix 'da-dum'. Underestimated and underutilised in B2B.\n- **Learn to Play the Long Game** — Consistency builds memory. Repetition isn't boring, it's a strategy. Hammer home a single simple message (durability, innovation, sustainability) until it's synonymous with your brand.\n- **Find Balance — the Long AND Short of it** — You can't choose between brand building and sales activation; you need both (see Binet & Field, 'The Long & the Short of it'). Brands that grow consistently master both: memorable enough to be chosen later, visible enough to be bought now.", "Take a fresh look at your brand. Assume no-one cares. How would you build a brand that lasts?"], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 8, "title": "Does B2B have a creativity problem?", "url": "/blog/does-b2b-have-a-creativity-problem", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "Spoiler alert… yes.", "paras": ["There's a perception that B2B marketing is a little boring and beige compared to the bright lights of B2C — and the research backs the hunch. System1, with LinkedIn's B2B Institute, tested 1,600 B2B ads across 6m people and found 77% score 1 out of 5 for creative effectiveness (vs around half of B2C ads). Yet 20 years of IPA effectiveness case studies show emotionally-led creative drives more positive business effects than rational advertising — and still B2B marketers are almost twice as likely to rely on 'rational', product-centric creative. This is driven partly by B2B's focus on short-term sales: LinkedIn data shows B2B marketers spend only ~8% of budgets on long-term brand awareness.", "B2B organisations are rarely marketing-led — sales or technical teams shout loudest, and the belief that product trumps brand means creativity gets dumped. Yet distinctive, entertaining and emotionally-led creative makes customers more likely to pay attention, purchase, and pay a premium.", "**Distinctiveness** — Mental availability: distinctive, memorable creative is more effective because only ~5% of a B2B audience are in-market at any one time. When customers are eventually in the market, they gravitate to brands they remember. The brand that gets remembered is the brand that gets bought — and you only get remembered by being distinctive. Deliver wallpaper and you don't.", "**Entertaining** — Humour works. It makes a brand relatable, demonstrates empathy, humanises, and makes an ad more memorable. Kantar's AdReaction study shows humour is the most powerful creative enhancer of receptivity; half their Creative Effectiveness Award winners used humour. 48% of B2B decision makers find B2B advertising boring, while 82% wish it had the creativity of B2C. \"Humour doesn't just help a brand stand out, it gets you in the gut.\" (Kantar)", "**Emotionally-led** — We underestimate the emotion tied up in B2B decisions. Harvard Business School has shown 95% of decision-making is subconscious. For B2B decision-makers the stakes are personal and high — get a procurement decision wrong and the consequences are far greater than a bad snack. \"Emotions are the fastest way to deepen memory structures that guide how we make purchasing decisions.\" (Kantar)", "**Up for the challenge?** — There's a clear link between creativity and effectiveness; most B2B businesses just haven't caught up. Getting stakeholders to buy into creativity isn't easy — the 'product delusion' is widespread. Ultimately it's our job as a creative agency to point marketing teams in the right direction and help them make the case for creativity."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 9, "title": "Tipping Point: Why it's time to embrace the full potential of trade influencers", "url": "/blog/tipping-point-why-its-time-to-embrace-the-full-potential-of-trade-influencers", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Influencer marketing isn't new — 75% of B2B marketers now use influencers in their mix. But most are only scratching the surface of the potential for brands in the built environment.", "**Why trade influencers matter** — Trade influencers were borne out of a specific need: connection in a world where many tradespeople work in isolation for long stretches. Most acute among younger trades, but older tradespeople increasingly use Instagram and Facebook to stay connected and learn. By building public profiles and communities, they share knowledge and showcase skills. That peer-to-peer validation is worth 100x more than any advert — especially for younger, sceptical audiences.", "**Making it meaningful** — Performance means everything. Unlike consumer influencers, any trade influencer worth their salt won't take cash from just anyone — their professional reputation hinges on who they work with. Get to know them, understand the products they use day-in day-out, and offer creative control so they can work with you authentically.", "**Cutting the strings** — Cover yourself with a proper agreement, but don't dictate the specifics of every piece of content. It needs to ring true to their public persona. This builds brand credibility through the voices of people who use your products every day. Treat them as collaborators and ambassadors, not contractors.", "**From strength to strength** — Platforms are evolving and peer-to-peer networks are becoming more powerful. Bricklaying has influencers with 100k+ Instagram followers and its own championship, Super Trowel — positioned more like a gaming convention than a trade event. Massive growth across plumbing, carpentry, and painting & decorating too.", "**So, what's next?** — Let go of a top-down marketing mindset and embrace collaboration. The question is no longer whether trade influencers matter, but whether your brand is ready to treat them as true partners.", "**Key Considerations:** The right partners (already love your products) · Take your time (understand their audience and tone) · Collaboration is key (tools and pointers, not scripts) · Rethink measurement (track referrals, product adoption, community sentiment) · Think long-term (real partnerships build authenticity over time)."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 10, "title": "CRM – Why customer perspective is key", "url": "/blog/crm-why-customer-perspective-is-key", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Customer Relationship Management — the clue is in the name, but brands often forget the customer should sit at the heart of any effective CRM strategy. Too often clients see CRM as a channel for pumping out products, saying what they want to say rather than what the customer wants to hear. Couple that with scatter-gun scheduling, no segmentation and a lack of data insight, and you switch customers off rather than building relationships.", "A well-engineered CRM strategy is a vital cog for long-term brand building. Done well, it reinforces brand messaging at every touch point, enhances experience, connects communities and deepens relationships — driving loyalty and advocacy. It should never be about 'sell, sell, sell!'.", "**Our core principle when building CRM strategies is relevancy.** Brands that do CRM well cut through the noise with content that's engaging but, most importantly, actually useful. We always start with the customer — flooding planning sessions with outside perspective (macro trends, topicality, content anchors, customer mindsets, barriers and opportunities) before developing comms that support their experience at any stage of the journey.", "Data plays a big role — the more we know, the more relevant we can be, which is why segmentation is vital for brands with diverse offerings and fragmented audiences. Contextual relevance matters too: internal feeds (like stock data) can update product content live; external APIs and geo-location can serve content based on when and where customers receive comms.", "A robust measurement and analysis framework is vital. We run regular measurement sessions with clients — deep dives into performance to ascertain creative effectiveness and build testing plans. Detailed analysis optimises performance and justifies spend, so KPIs should be defined from the outset and tailored to each communication. The goal: a cycle of continual improvement where performance data informs strategy, which informs content and creative — analysing, testing and learning every cycle."], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 11, "title": "Putting Co-Design at the heart of UX/UI  (a.k.a. Creative Masterclass: UX Design)", "url": "/blog/creative-masterclass-ux-design", "type": "Perspective / How-to", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["As design challenges become more complex, so does the need to align to user needs and expectations. The pandemic accelerated our need to work together collaboratively. When designing any digital experience, put the end-user at the heart — but go beyond standard research and an 'us and them' approach. **'Co-design'** is a collaborative methodology that digs into the perspectives of internal and external stakeholders to co-create experiences that create equal value for company and customer.", "Break UX down into three parts: **UR (User Research), UX (User Experience Design) and UI (User Interface Design).**", "**Starting with UR** — Involve people with different perspectives early and regularly. The objective is to capture and translate user insights into meaningful experiences — starting by identifying core user groups including, crucially, sceptics, brand 'passengers' and advocates. Don't underestimate internal stakeholders (frontline teams help identify the right users to research). A dedicated User Researcher streamlines recruitment. Principles: *Go wide* (find clarity on core groups; insights from non-subscribers matter as much as fans) · *Be prepared to get uncomfortable* (avoid assumptions, ask open-ended questions, ask 'why' not 'what/how') · *Share and test findings early* (be iterative; don't wait for 'ta-dah' moments).", "**Moving forward with UX** — Take research findings, plus business and brand strategy, and develop a sitemap and information architecture — collaboratively with client and users. Low-fidelity prototyping on key tasks keeps structure user-centred. **Producing clickable wireframe prototypes is an efficient testing mechanism that later translates into high-level design concepts** — letting users be objective about the task without creative distractions, and letting the UX designer address changes live and re-test efficiently.", "**Connecting the creative dots with UI** — The most subjective stage: interface your brand's distinctive assets with the user journey. Investment in understanding user motivations pays dividends here. Brand guidelines aren't always fit for digital — colours, fonts and styles don't always translate, causing accessibility issues that must be flushed out. Test and validate with core users until you find the balance of stimulating creativity and frictionless functionality.", "**Playing the long game** — User testing should be permanent; once launched, every website needs a continual improvement process to stay a true reflection of the brand and chime with the changing needs of the audience."], "pillar": "How-To"}, {"n": 12, "title": "Build it and they will come? Only if it offers genuine experience", "url": "/blog/build-it-and-they-will-come-only-if-it-offers-genuine-experience", "type": "Perspective / interview (Material Source Studio)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Darren Clanford & Michael Rogan, co-founders of Material Source Studio, introduce their concept changing the future of built-environment and commercial interior specification. A three-minute walk from Manchester's Victoria Station, at 1 Federation Street in the Grade II listed Hanover Building, Material Source Studio is the first of its kind offering a holistic offline/online experience for architects, designers, makers and property professionals.", "**A holistic experience** — In 2018, creative director Darren Clanford co-founded materialsource.co.uk, an online resource celebrating materials and the people who bring them to life, always planning to translate it into an immersive real-world experience. Michael brought operational expertise; both agreed the first site had to be Manchester — \"an incomparable irreverent confidence that we want to harness.\" The doors opened in 2021 to a ready-and-waiting community craving tactility and collaboration after lockdown.", "**A creative toolbox** — \"A toolbox for the North West — a place where the architecture and design community can meet, share ideas and collaborate\" (Michael Rogan). Across two levels: exhibits from 40+ leading brands, an 80-seat theatre, CPD area, 300+ book library, 7 meeting spaces, a co-working hub, a podcast studio, an internal garden with a 6-metre tree, and a seasonally-changing gallery.", "**Doing things differently** — Commercial director David Smalley: \"What we're offering is exponential value for our community. As we enter a new world where we do things differently, why not make things better than before?\" Endorsed by visitors including Monika Swindells (Monika Studio) and Stevie Leigh (Fairhursts Design Group).", "**What's next?** — With Manchester gaining momentum, attention turns to next destinations. Architects and designers are more time-poor than ever and keen to experience what's new, efficiently and sustainably. Material Source Studio is a physical response to 30+ years of direct conversation with architects and designers."], "pillar": "5 in 5"}, {"n": 13, "title": "Why the office matters – A view from the Creative Agency", "url": "/blog/why-the-office-matters-a-view-from-the-agency", "type": "Perspective / agency culture", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Creative Industries businesses have always been more flexible on workplace environment, and there's real advantage in embracing the changes of the last couple of years. Remaining agile and adaptable has worked well: plenty of collaborative space, hot desks, quiet rooms and communal areas — designed for both collaborative creative spark and more formal strategic thinking. The challenge has been developing this across office and WFH; investing in the right technology became non-negotiable early on.", "Incremental updates to the office interior have created a constant-improvement vibe, and combined with a flexible hybrid week (with a few core rules for collaboration) has enhanced a culture that celebrates individuality and creativity while preserving productivity. The rural location, creative space and agency culture is an increasingly attractive proposition to previously city-dwelling talent. \"The happier everyone is at work, the better quality work is produced. Our office environment is pivotal to that — like holding up a mirror, reflecting out our culture and values.\""], "pillar": "Perspective"}, {"n": 14, "title": "Working Towards a new Sustainability  (5-in-5 interview + Brand Experts view)", "url": "/blog/working-towards-a-new-sustainability", "type": "Perspective / 5-in-5 interview", "subtitle": "(Note: /blog/working-towards-a-new-sustainability-a-view-from-the-brand-experts appears to be the companion/second half of this same piece.)", "paras": ["A perfect storm — the pandemic, climate change, Brexit, social inequalities — has fundamentally shifted customer perspective and motivations. Built Environment organisations are in the eye of the storm: supply chain disruption, skilled labour shortages, shrinking margins, and now increasing accountability on environmental and community impact. Now is not the time for poignant posts and carefully selected hashtags — brands need to dig deeper. A **5-in-5 interview** with Regenerative Provocateur and Consultant **Martin Brown**:", "- **Q1 (urgency):** We're witnessing weather patterns we thought belonged to the future, at only 1.2°C warming. Action has to be a 'whole of society' response — no one can opt out. Advice for brands: 'Act Now'. For our sector, a significant contributor to climate change, it's non-negotiable.\n- **Q2 (is a Sustainability Policy enough?):** The 1987 Brundtland definition of sustainability has failed to arrest climate and ecological collapse. Words like eco, sustainable and green have become empty, enabling greenwashing. Question whether your actions are degenerative or regenerative.\n- **Q3 (making the difference):** Regenerative thinking won't give a magic formula but enables better questions — shifting from product sustainability to a regenerative brand culture, focusing on potential not just problems, so organisations thrive as part of, not apart from, natural living systems.\n- **Q4 (demonstrating commitment):** Be transparent; link to existing reporting, verify through ISO 14001, B Corp or similar. Product transparency via the Declare label (International Living Future Institute) — the 'food label' equivalent for the built environment.\n- **Q5 (best advice):** Develop a regenerative culture — incremental improvements without shying from transformational action. One of the biggest opportunities we've ever had, needing authentic passion, creativity, disruption and real leadership.", "**A view from the Brand Experts — Nicky Jepson, Marketing Director:** *The Re-generation of Brands.* Successful brands are only as good as their relevance, and climate change is now non-negotiable and a key purchase driver.\n- **Get perspective** — Loyalties are only as good as your relevancy right now. Best aesthetic design won't save a product that can't be recycled. Data only takes you so far — walk a mile in your customers' shoes.\n- **Think beyond sustainability** — Sustainability alone won't cut it. Genuinely regenerative brands are already ahead — eye on the future, long-term brand equity over short-term profit, investing in innovation and creative leadership.\n- **Be authentically passionate** — Martin (spoke at COP26): \"Be clear and accountable about your claims and intentions.\" Customers, future workforce and stakeholders are experts at sniffing out authenticity. An opportunity to stand up and be counted, not tick a 'sustainable' box."], "pillar": "5 in 5"}, {"n": 15, "title": "Underlay brand 'feels like nothing on earth' in new creative campaign", "url": "/blog/underlay-brand-feels-like-nothing-on-earth-in-new-creative-campaign", "type": "News (campaign)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Workhouse created **Interfloor's first-ever consumer/retailer brand campaign** for its **Tredaire** carpet underlay range. Three 30\" CGI ads featuring the 'Tredaire-nauts' floating through space, strapline **'Feels like nothing on earth'**, set to *Cosmic Dancer* by T.Rex. Launched on Channel 4 during George Clarke's Remarkable Renovations (24 April), across radio, digital and in-store, in two bursts (Apr–Jun, Sep–Nov). Collaborators: Flipbook Studio (animation), Media Performance (media). Quotes from Lynn Bamber (Interfloor Marketing Director) and **Tom Gathercole (Strategy & Growth Lead, Workhouse)**."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 16, "title": "12 Ways of Us: A Christmas campaign built on connection", "url": "/blog/12-ways-of-us", "type": "News (agency culture / campaign)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Workhouse's Christmas campaign, ideated around the table in the **Ribchester office** with every department represented. **'The 12 Ways of Us'** — 12 individual festive video portraits featuring every team member (shot with Studio Dark in a converted garage studio), run as a 12-day Instagram series. Instead of client gifts, they supported **Re-engage**, the charity reducing loneliness in later life. Theme: creativity and connection live in every person in the agency."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 17, "title": "Ten Years of B Corp. Three Years of Us. And We're Only Just Getting Started.", "url": "/blog/ten-years-of-b-corp-three-years-of-us-and-were-only-just-getting-started", "type": "News (B Corp)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Marks 10 years of B Corp in the UK; **Workhouse B Corp certified since 2023.** 10 milestones: 3 completed B Impact Assessments; local milkman switch (saved 895+ plastic containers); 65% waste recycled; people-first OKRs/promotions; on-site beehive + bug hotel; Photoshop/Illustrator training at a local Deaf School (Simon & Rianna); a Schools Biodiversity Project; **The Workhouse Academy** (learning programme led by Simon Preece & Clare Roberts); mentoring other businesses through B Corp; **carbon neutral for three years.** Proud to stand alongside 2,500+ UK B Corps."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 18, "title": "Workhouse recognised for Design in The Drum Honours", "url": "/blog/workhouse-recognised-for-design-in-the-drum-honours", "type": "News (award)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Workhouse placed in **The Drum Honours Top 10 Design Agencies** (2025 global awards data), alongside Mother, Design Bridge and Code & Theory. Positioning line worth reusing: *\"design at Workhouse has never been about decoration. It's about clarity. About making complex, technical worlds feel human… especially in the Built Environment, where great creative is often overlooked and underestimated.\"*"], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 19, "title": "A silver celebration: The Drum Marketing Awards EMEA", "url": "/blog/a-silver-celebration-making-our-mark-at-the-drum-marketing-awards-emea", "type": "News (award)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Two nominations, one Silver. Shortlisted **'Brilliant use of advertising'** for the Interfloor Tredaire campaign (alongside Nike, Tiffany & Co, Unilever, Sky Mobile); **won Silver for 'Excellence in design/brand'** for the **rebrand of Forbes Solicitors** (against Renault, Typhoo, Diageo, Breville, M&S). Philosophy line: *\"big ideas don't just belong to big brands.\"*"], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 20, "title": "Workhouse bag BIMA award (for their work with Peldon Rose)", "url": "/blog/workhouse-pick-up-bima-award-for-their-work-with-peldon-rose", "type": "News (award)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Won a **Bronze at the 2023 BIMA Awards** (the UK's longest-standing digital/tech awards, est. 1985) for work with **Peldon Rose**, London's leading office design & build experts."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 21, "title": "Workhouse joins growing B Corp movement", "url": "/blog/workhouse-joins-growing-b-corp-movement", "type": "News (B Corp — original certification announcement)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Certification announcement. **Managing Director Martin Meadows:** \"We're incredibly proud of this certification… the opportunity to supercharge our creativity to do business for good.\" Covers five impact areas (Governance, Workers, Community, Environment, Customers); Workhouse legally embedded \"purpose beyond profit\" in its company articles. Specialists in the Built Environment, \"a palpable movement to address social and environmental responsibilities.\""], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 22, "title": "Continuing to build out our Manchester office with new development duo", "url": "/blog/continuing-to-build-out-our-manchester-office-with-new-development-duo", "type": "News (hires)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["New digital engineering hires: **Raul Sanz** (Front-End Developer, ex Ogilvy & Mather, Lola MullenLowe, JD Sports) and **Valerie Oni** (Senior Developer). Quotes from **John Paul Toher (Head of Digital)** and **Martin Meadows (MD)**. Notes \"deep roots in Lancashire's Ribble Valley\" plus \"a growing base in central Manchester\", and initiatives Best Companies and B Corp."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 23, "title": "Workhouse appointed to develop online strategy for Peldon Rose", "url": "/blog/workhouse-appointed-to-develop-online-strategy-for-peldon-rose", "type": "News (new business)", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Appointed by **Peldon Rose** (London workplace design & build) after a competitive pitch to build a new online home to attract and convert clients. Quotes from **Nicky Jepson (Marketing Director)** and Danielle Emery (Head of Marketing, Peldon Rose)."], "pillar": "News"}, {"n": 24, "title": "Working Towards a new Sustainability – A view from the Brand Experts", "url": "/blog/working-towards-a-new-sustainability-a-view-from-the-brand-experts", "type": "Perspective", "subtitle": "", "paras": ["Companion piece to #14 — Nicky Jepson's \"The Re-generation of Brands\" brand-expert commentary (Get perspective · Think beyond sustainability · Be authentically passionate). Captured in full within #14 above."], "pillar": "Perspective"}];